    {
      "id": "310da182bf72da02bd01a94b71411d31cba06cb0",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2017-12-04 01:16:14.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nIt looks like the low-level staffs is still async?  It might be useful to have a test that adds a fail_loc delay to statfs, then check that “df” with the delay is still a single delay period and not $OSTCOUNT delay periods. Otherwise, on very large filesystems serialized statfs would take a long time.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "bc4de10f11b0c011f6a2f0cbcff5de79239cbd31",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 177,
        "name": "John Hammond",
        "email": "jhammond@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "jhammond"
      },
      "date": "2017-12-04 15:57:51.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n> It looks like the low-level staffs is still async?\n\nCorrect. We are only removing a callback that was fired when the request set completed and doing what the callback did after returning from ptlrpc_set_wait().\n\n> It might be useful to have a test that adds a fail_loc delay to statfs, then check that “df” with the delay is still a single delay period and not $OSTCOUNT delay periods. Otherwise, on very large filesystems serialized statfs would take a long time.\n\nOK.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
